	<div id="p4863" class="post bg2">
		<div class="inner">

		<div class="postbody">
			

			<h3 ><a href="#p4863"></a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="./viewtopic.php?p=4863#p4863"><img src="./styles/modestus/imageset/icon_post_target.png" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>by <strong><a href="./memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=4">zcorpan</a></strong> &raquo; Fri Mar 13, 2009 8:46 am </p>

			

			<div class="content">We can't make &lt;img&gt; a container element because of legacy -- all pages on the Web that use &lt;img&gt; today would break. We can't introduce &lt;image&gt; as a container element, either, because there are pages out there that have &lt;image&gt; and expect to be treated as &lt;img&gt;.
<br />
<br />If you want rich fallback for images, use &lt;object&gt;. If the image is purely decorative, you could use CSS3 generated content:
<br />
<br /><dl class="codebox"><dt>Code: <a href="#" onclick="selectCode(this); return false;">Select all</a></dt><dd><code>&lt;h1&gt;Foo &lt;strong&gt;bar&lt;/strong&gt; baz&lt;/h1&gt;</code></dd></dl><dl class="codebox"><dt>Code: <a href="#" onclick="selectCode(this); return false;">Select all</a></dt><dd><code>h1 &#123; content:url&#40;foo.png&#41; &#125;</code></dd></dl>
<br />
<br /><blockquote><div><cite>Ritz wrote:</cite>I have discovered that &lt;canvas&gt; already works the way I was proposing &lt;img&gt; or &lt;image&gt; might work. Right now that code validates, but I do notice some language that discourages the kind of use I've just implemented:</div></blockquote>I think it's equally discouraged as using &lt;img&gt; here, but currently the alternatives that work cross-browser aren't great either, so I would say that for now it's fine.</div>

			

		</div>

		
			<dl class="postprofile" id="profile4863">
			<dt>
				<a href="./memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=4">zcorpan</a>
			</dt>

			<dd>&lt;article&gt;</dd>

